### 2. Forensic Payload Analysis & Threat Intel Pivoting
By expanding the raw JSON log payload of the triggered event, I extracted the critical static Indicators of Compromise (IoCs) generated by the FIM engine:


json
"syscheck": {
    "path": "c:\\lab-fim\\mimikatz.exe",
    "event": "added",
    "uname": "vboxuser",
    "md5": "[Your real mimikatz MD5 hash from the JSON view]",
    "sha256": "[Your real mimikatz SHA256 hash from the JSON view]"
}

The Triage Workflow
Context Differentiation: While normal user activity generates "data drift," the creation of an executable binary in a non-standard directory immediately shifts the priority level.

Hash Extraction: As a SOC Analyst, I targeted the syscheck.sha256 value from the raw JSON payload.

Threat Intelligence Query: Pivoting this unique cryptographic signature against open-source intelligence platforms like VirusTotal yields an immediate, overwhelming match for a classified malicious tool (HackTool.Mimikatz).

Verdict: This validates the alert as a True Positive, empowering the incident response team to immediately authorize host isolation procedures.


🧠 Strategic Retrospective & Engineering Takeaways
Defense-in-Depth and Compensating Controls: This project highlights that a SOC engineer cannot rely on a single source of truth. When EDR or behavioral tools (Sysmon) are blocked by OS architectural limitations, a granularly configured FIM engine can effectively serve as a high-fidelity tripwire.

Operational Realities over Theory: Building this laboratory exposed me to the harsh realities of enterprise security engineering: dealing with missing OS updates, broken dependencies, locked sockets, and deprecated cryptographic protocol baselines.

Future Hardening (Active Response Automation): The next logical iteration of this project is the integration of automated workflows. By mapping a high-severity FIM alert matching known malicious directories to a Wazuh Active Response script, the manager can instantly execute an automated endpoint PowerShell command to isolate the host network adapter interface, mitigating the risk of lateral movement long before human analyst intervention.
